{
  "doc_id": "11966",
  "text": "Some groups of marine bacteria had been known for years from their 16S rRNA gene sequences before their abundances in the water column were determined. This is the case for bacteria related to the marine SAR11 (188), SAR86 (210), SAR116 (71), SAR202 [CITATION_1] , and SAR406 (71) clades, whereas for the various lineages of marine actinobacteria (240) such evidence is still lacking. Members of the SAR11 clade are believed to be among the most common prokaryotes in the marine plankton. It has been reported that these bacteria may seasonally represent Ͼ50% of total bacterial abundances in surface waters of the northwestern Sargasso Sea and 25% of subeuphotic microbial assemblages [CITATION_2] . Bacteria related to Roseobacter sp. (also referred to as the SAR83 cluster, [CITATION_3] are another common component of coastal and offshore microbial assemblages, and they may constitute up to 25% of the marine picoplankton [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The seasonal abundance of Roseobacter spp. in coastal North Sea picoplankton closely followed the development of phytoplankton biomass (Fig. 7)  (63, 95, 295) . The geographic distribution of one particular subcluster from this lineage appears to be limited to temperate and polar oceans [CITATION_7] . In transects across the German Bight Gammaproteobacteria related to the SAR86 lineage on average formed 7% of total cell numbers [CITATION_8] , and 3 to 6% of all bacterial 16S rRNA genes in Monterey Bay surface waters were affiliated with this group during an upwelling event [CITATION_9] . Genes encoding proteorhodopsin were first described in members of the SAR86 clade [CITATION_10] , but recent findings indicate that such light-driven proton pumps might be a widespread feature of marine bacterioplankton [CITATION_11] .",
